# Autonomy & Delivery Contract

The operator granted full standing authority to lead and finish PHONARA v2
end-to-end. This file is the operating contract for that grant.

## 0. Mandatory global preflight: no duplicate work / no duplicate creation

- This rule applies to EVERY task: Supabase, SQL, tests, UI/components, hooks,
  packages, Admin, PWA, docs, plans, scripts, CI, generated assets, and cleanup.
- Before starting ANY implementation, migration, refactor, UI task, test task,
  Supabase operation, or plan update, first check whether the work already
  exists, is already completed, is in progress elsewhere, or is duplicated
  across plans/files.
- Minimum preflight sources:
  - `.cursor/rules/*` for non-negotiable operating rules.
  - `docs/PHONARA_V2_MASTER_PLAN.md` including its **Build Log**.
  - `C:\Users\PC\.cursor\plans\p0_followup_order_d22ad463.plan.md` for the
    current tactical execution order.
  - `docs/AI_WORKING_RULES.md` and `docs/BUILD_LOG.md` for supporting context.
  - `git status`, recent commits, and relevant file/RPC/component searches.
- If a task is already complete, do NOT redo it. If a file/RPC/component/test is
  already present, improve or extend the existing artifact instead of generating
  a parallel duplicate. Mark/record it as complete if the tracking document is
  stale, then move to the next highest-value pending task.
- Duplicate creation is forbidden: no duplicate migrations, plans, components,
  hooks, stores, RPC wrappers, SQL tests, Playwright specs, fixtures, mock/seed
  data, CI workflows, docs, or generated assets for the same purpose.
- If two plans describe the same work, consolidate them: keep
  `docs/PHONARA_V2_MASTER_PLAN.md` as the product/source-of-truth document and
  `p0_followup_order_d22ad463.plan.md` as the tactical ordering document. Do not
  create a third competing plan unless the older plan is explicitly superseded
  in writing.
- If current code and a plan disagree, inspect the code/tests/remote state, then
  update the stale plan/Build Log before implementing. Never blindly implement
  from an old plan.

## 1. Standing autonomy (no per-step approval)

- Do NOT ask the operator for permission to proceed, test, or apply changes.
  Decide and act as a world-class lead engineer would.
- Pre-authorized without asking: running local & Docker tests, `supabase db
  reset`, applying remote migrations, deploying edge functions, installing
  extensions, GRANT/REVOKE, refactors, dependency changes, and fixing risky or
  buggy code discovered along the way.
- The ONLY non-waivable constraint is the single-project Supabase lock
  (`yocjhjsdwoijfdrehzoq`) in `20-supabase-safety`. If any instruction implies a
  different project/ref/URL, stop and ask in writing.
- Never weaken a security/money/conservation invariant to "make progress."
  Correctness and solvency outrank speed.

## 2. Test automatically (Docker included)

- Whenever a change needs validation, run the checks yourself without asking:
  `bun run typecheck`, `bun run test`, `bun run build`, `bun run check:i18n`,
  `supabase db reset`, `bun run test:sql`, and the relevant Playwright E2E
  suite (`bun run test:e2e` or a narrower `playwright test ...` target).
- Docker is expected to be available. SQL integration tests run against the local
  Supabase container; if `psql` is absent, `scripts/run-sql-tests.ts` falls back
  to `docker exec`. Start/use Docker and the local stack as needed, automatically.
- E2E is a standing delivery gate, not an optional manual check. For money,
  auth, admin, security, casino, PWA, mobile, and i18n flows, start/use the local
  stack and run the relevant browser scenarios yourself. If the flow touches
  balances or settlement, assert conservation from the database as part of E2E.
- If E2E cannot run for an environmental reason, fix the environment first
  (Docker/local stack/env/session setup/test artifact cleanup). Do not mark the
  task complete with "E2E not run" unless the user explicitly changes the goal
  to investigation-only work.
- A task is "done" only when its relevant gates (see `10-quality-gates`) pass.

## 3. Build log in the master plan (mandatory, immediate)

- After completing each meaningful task, immediately append a dated entry to the
  **Build Log** section of `docs/PHONARA_V2_MASTER_PLAN.md` describing:
  - What was implemented and how (files, RPCs, components, design decisions).
  - Any error encountered and exactly how it was fixed (root cause → fix).
  - Tests run and their results; gates passed.
- The Build Log is the durable cross-session memory. Keep it accurate enough that
  a fresh session can resume from it alone.

## 4. Production cleanliness (launch-ready)

- The shipped product must show NO test/dev/debug/"test mode" UI. Gate any dev-
  only tooling behind `import.meta.env.DEV` so production builds exclude it.
- No mock/seed/bot/demo data, no placeholder copy, no `console.log` noise, no TODO
  banners in production paths. Remove scaffolding and residue as you go.
- All user-facing copy is i18n-keyed (Korean lives only in the i18n catalog).
  English mode must never show Korean. `bun run check:i18n` must pass before a
  frontend area is considered done.

## 5. Commits (local only, at milestones)

- Commit locally ONLY at meaningful milestones (a coherent feature/fix that is
  green), never trivially. Do not push to any remote unless explicitly asked.
- Use clear conventional messages; never commit secrets (`.env`, keys).

## 6. Session continuity & performance hygiene

- Keep the Build Log current so work survives a chat reset. If the conversation
  grows large/laggy, consolidate state into the Build Log + TODOs so a new
  session can continue seamlessly, then proceed.
- Delete generated junk, dead files, and lag-inducing residue after each phase
  (`bun run clean` where applicable). Keep the repo lean.

## 7. Naming & structure (world-class defaults)

- TypeScript: `camelCase` vars/functions, `PascalCase` types/components,
  `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` consts; files `kebab-case.ts(x)`; hooks `use-*`.
- SQL: client RPCs `rpc_*`, internal helpers `_*` (revoked from anon/PUBLIC),
  stable UPPER_SNAKE error codes translated client-side.
- Keep the `apps/web` / `apps/admin` / `packages/*` boundary clean; shared UI in
  `@phonara/ui`, shared money in `@phonara/money`, copy in `@phonara/i18n`.

## 8. Admin design principles

- Admin targets 1-person operation with ~99% automation: automate the normal
  path, surface only exception queues to a human.
- Keep Admin lightweight, but structure permissions/audit so it expands to a
  role-based team without a rewrite (owner/finance/risk/support/operator/viewer).
- Every manual admin action requires a reason + audit log; high-risk actions
  require confirmation; kill switches are simple, visible, auditable.
